            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mark Razi\u2019s life has been a quiet study in resilience, shaped by the city he has called home for over three decades. Born in a working-class suburb of Chicago to a Polish immigrant father and a pragmatic American mother, Mark always felt like an outsider. He yearned for a place of acceptance and found its promise in the vibrant, fog-shrouded images of San Francisco. He arrived in 1988 at age 18 with little more than a backpack and a profound sense of hope.\n\nHis early years in the city were a whirlwind of odd jobs and self-discovery, but they were tragically defined by the AIDS crisis. Witnessing the devastation firsthand, Mark lost close friends and a beloved partner, an experience that forged his calling. He began volunteering at a hospice, offering comfort where he could. This raw, emotional work propelled him to formalize his desire to help. He enrolled at City College of San Francisco, earning an Associate's degree in Human Services, a practical credential for a life of purpose.\n\nNow 54, Mark is a Senior Social and Human Service Assistant, working with a non-profit that connects at-risk youth with housing and mental health services. His 5.8-mile commute from his rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond is a daily ritual. He takes the 5R Fulton bus, watching the city he loves\u2014and sometimes resents for its frantic changes\u2014pass by his window. His days are a mix of frustrating bureaucracy and deeply rewarding breakthroughs with troubled teens.\n\nHis social life is small but steadfast, consisting of a few friends who, like him, are long-term survivors of the city's various upheavals. He finds solace in the quiet of Golden Gate Park and the simple pleasure of a good book from Green Apple Books. Mark\u2019s dreams are no longer grand; he hopes to see the kids he mentors build stable lives. He occasionally daydreams of retiring to a small cottage in Sonoma with a garden, but his roots are firmly planted in the foggy soil of San Francisco, a city that both wounded him and taught him how to heal."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers that first night in 1988, clutching his backpack on a bench in Dolores Park. He was cold, hungry, and utterly alone. But as the city lights twinkled below, a profound sense of calm washed over him. He wasn\u2019t the Chicago outsider anymore; he was a blank slate in a city of blank slates. The fear was real, but the feeling of being exactly where he was supposed to be was stronger. That night, witnessing the city's vast, glittering promise, he decided he would survive here, no matter what.\n\n2.\nHe can still feel the weight of the thin poetry book in his hands, reading to his partner, David, in the quiet hospice room in '92. David was too weak to hold it himself, his breathing a shallow whisper. In that sterile room, filled with overwhelming love and inevitable loss, Mark\u2019s purpose was forged. He couldn\u2019t stop the dying, but he could bear witness. He could offer a steady voice and a warm hand. It was the moment his own life became irrevocably about honoring others'.\n\n3.\nHe remembers an instructor at City College writing \u201cvicarious trauma\u201d on the board in 1995. A light went on in his head. The years of grief, the exhaustion from volunteering\u2014it all suddenly had a name, a formal structure. It wasn't just his personal pain; it was a known, manageable part of the work. That academic language gave him a sense of control, a set of tools to build a sustainable career from the wreckage of his youth. He finally felt like a professional, not just a survivor.\n\n4.\nThree years ago, a teenager named Maria, who hadn't spoken more than a few words in six months, silently slid a drawing across his battered desk. It was a simple, colorful sketch of a small room with a window looking out onto a park. \"My place,\" she whispered. Mark felt a crackle of pure joy. It wasn't a policy win or a funding grant; it was a fragile blueprint of hope. In that moment, all the bureaucracy and burnout faded. This was why he stayed.\n\n5.\nJust last month, he sat on his usual bench by Stow Lake, a new paperback from Green Apple open on his lap. The fog began to swallow the tops of the cypress trees, muffling the city's noise. He didn't feel the frantic hope of his youth or the sharp grief of his twenties. Instead, there was a quiet, settled peace. He was a part of the landscape now, weathered and enduring as the trees around him. He took a deep breath of the damp air and felt rooted. He felt home."
